%% Mermaid sequence diagram — one for the happy path, one or two for critical failure paths.
%% Use `autonumber` so reviewers can reference steps. Label every cross-component edge with the operation name.
%% Make middleware stack visible at the gateway (AuthN → AuthZ → RateLimit → Trace).
%% Note async edges with a `Note` block — the reader needs to see where the synchronous response separates from the async commit.

sequenceDiagram
    autonumber
    participant <<P1>> as <<Participant 1 (e.g., Client)>>
    participant <<P2>> as <<Participant 2 (e.g., API Gateway)>>
    participant <<P3>> as <<Participant 3 (e.g., Cart)>>
    participant <<P4>> as <<Participant 4 (e.g., Downstream)>>

    <<P1>>->><<P2>>: <<request — e.g., POST /resource (Idempotency-Key)>>
    <<P2>>->><<P2>>: <<middleware stack — AuthN · AuthZ · RateLimit · Trace>>
    <<P2>>->><<P3>>: <<forwarded operation>>
    <<P3>>->><<P4>>: <<downstream call>>
    <<P4>>-->><<P3>>: <<downstream response>>
    <<P3>>-->><<P2>>: <<response>>
    <<P2>>-->><<P1>>: <<200 + body>>

    Note over <<P3>>: <<async work split — e.g., outbox commit; event publishes within Ns of HTTP 200>>

